Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars related, that is, arising from a single cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and they can be read briefly on the university's website.
The cause of the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent stirring in the clouds of gas that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of birth and the region of formation of stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulation carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer simulated two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
This object, under the influence of its own gravity, transforms over several million years into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added label paints to the initial gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieves a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to search for relative stars by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
