Recalling the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect trade unions as a civil right.
“Where there are trade unions, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is the Co-Chair of the Progressive Party Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to present the Workers’ Rights Enlargement Act along with the civil rights movement’s symbol, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade unions as it does against other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of union opponents.
The amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to enable workers who face discrimination for participation in trade union organizations to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and fines - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Ellison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these purposes will be recognized as illegal.
When the former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chair of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a global agreement, Roosevelt and its constituents had the right to include in their treaties a guarantee that "everyone has the right to
For generations, Americans have taken as a proper basis that labor rights are human rights.
When this country consulted other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions – and to have this trade union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government institutions – must be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to be organized and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade unions - has long since matured.
Keith Allison and John Lewis revive the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Close All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana
In the U.S., a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the Louisiana law, which his supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginald in June and was due to enter into force on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to admit patients to a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that for the time being, doctors can continue to make legal abortions while continuing to seek such powers.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing to exercise their powers,” Judge John deGrevells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will be appointed within a month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision under this law.
Advocates of the right to abortion welcomed this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital credentials.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northap, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to stop the law from three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who had not been the plaintiffs in the case, and also filed an application for admission authority.
Louisiana is among the 11 states that have passed such laws, and the courts recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to an abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that laws on admission powers impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortions object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has the authority to be admitted to a hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions until their applications for admissions authority await a decision.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas for domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of goods in the assortment of trade networks should be of Russian production, says the deputy of the State Duma from the faction "Fair Russia" Oleg Nilov.
