This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. <0x3C>...> According to the rest of the product groups that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers," - Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the basics of state regulation of commercial activity in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for the introduction of amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced rate of VAT of 10% on the sale of products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in trade networks is part of the package of incentives for Russian manufacturers.
At the counters will appear several times more domestic goods.
However, the initiative can have both a positive and a negative effect, experts say.
According to Sergei Litvinenko, a lawyer at Taxovik, a member of the independent expert center of the Public Duma, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive and will lead to growth.
In addition, there will be agricultural producers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that the profit will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian producers will be able to increase their activity and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be faster to master, and contribute to GDP growth.
Russia’s dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately,” the expert notes.
Previously, Russian companies often could not break into the counters of local stores due to high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, after the introduction of the embargo, this niche has been liberated and can be sighed with relief.
But it should not be forgotten that after all the necessary agreements and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now is the "moment of silence" when the previous players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products," said the first Vice-President of the All-Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", c.e. Tamara Kasyanova.
Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will help to consolidate the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that, at the expense of subsidies from another state, are cheaper.
In other words, the fight for the buyer will unfold between companies working according to the uniform laws of the industry.
On the other hand, according to Kasyanova, Russian producers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots by far not in all articles.
And in this situation, the trade networks will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that low-quality goods will come to the counters.
Possibly, under the guise of produced in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be delivered," the expert adds.
The negative effect of quotas will be felt by large trade networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that with such a schedule, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, as the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods can also affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to wind up prices on the second, as on a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, economists spoke again in February of this year because of the continuing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more relevant.
The law is intended to oblige retailers in the formation of orders suppliers to deal with domestic manufacturers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and a system of production planning for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," says Deputy Oleg Nilov.
A particularly effective quota mechanism would be for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example in the dairy sector where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to completely cover the counters of Russian shops.
In addition, a powerful impulse can also be given to meat production.
As you know, the largest share of imports is for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still belongs to Russian products," Kasyanova says.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will facilitate import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, as this requires a complex of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that a full import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, there is little to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to meet these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide," the expert notes.
Early diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more.
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video commemorating their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women pardoning in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with "ovarian cancer" in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research reported that the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
FAR MORE INVESTIGATION: New drugs may slow down lung cancer and ovarian cancer
The researchers tracked the medical path of women for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said the woman’s age at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases, and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside of cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that early diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of outgoing services that will allow specialists to treat women closer to home and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, emphasizing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elishe Nive, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
