Production growth in the euro area slowed to its lowest in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest value of the business activity index (PMI) of the manufacturing sector of the euro area according to Markit fell to 50.7 in August, falling from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates growth.
New orders have been delayed and businesses have suffered amid rising tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures came before the meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will expect a clear plan from the bank as to how to deal with the halting of the eurozone recovery, as well as the threat of deflation with inflation of only 0.3%.
There is speculation that ECB chief Mario Draghi may give additional signals later this week that he is considering a quantitative easing scheme for the euro area similar to those used by the UK and the US during the financial crisis.
“Although some growth is better than no growth at all, the slowing effect of growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty on producers is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, senior economist at Markit.
The PMI of Germany’s manufacturing sector, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its 11-month low of 51.4.
Meanwhile, in the bloc’s second-largest economy, France, PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to cause real concern, as does Italy’s weakening from steady growth to stagnation.
Signs that the growth momentum has faded mainly from the industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also do not add to confidence,” said Dobson.
The industry’s slowdown is likely to still fuel analysts waiting to introduce additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news was from Ireland, where PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since the end of 1999.
Howard Archer, Chief Economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August study of the Eurozone business activity index is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “The producers of the euro zone obviously find life very difficult at the moment, as the current increased geopolitical tension – especially related to Russia/Ukraine – adds uncertainty to the still difficult conditions in many countries.
This heightened tension has obviously hit the business — and especially the consumer confidence — and likely leads to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
