Twitter is trying to make it more interesting for new users.
The microblogging service Twitter has changed the user registration process to involve new participants more quickly in active interaction with the platform.
This measure should reduce the number of people who have abandoned their microblogs.
Now, new Twitter users will view a large number of accounts recommended by the service during registration to immediately make up their reading circle.
Recommendations are made on the basis of the interests indicated in the registration.
At the same time, Twitter automatically sets a subscription tick for all automatically selected accounts.
Because of this, the user will have to remove the ticks himself, so as not to read those who are not interested in him.
If previously microblogging users only saw avatars of recommended users, now Twitter takes a sample of one of the blogger’s popular tweets to help make an impression about a person.
This is the biggest change to Twitter’s registration page in three years.
Recently, Twitter is actively working on the modernization of the service.
Such activity is primarily related to the ongoing attempts of the service to achieve losslessness.
In 2014, the microblogging service faced a slowdown in user base growth and a decline in reader activity.
The company is now desperately in need of more loyal consumer resources, which, once in a while, would have stayed for a long time.
This is the only way to ensure a stable flow of advertising funds.
