Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis is rooted in 2006, when the army removed the Prime Minister of his brother Yinglyk Chinawat Taksin.
Both are popular with the rural population, especially in the northern parts of the country, which has ensured them success in elections.
However, many representatives of the middle class and the capital’s elite have entered an anti-government movement that has virtually paralyzed the country since November 2013.
