A genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed.
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking she was going to die after being misdiagnosed.
Karin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking that she had only a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Sharko-Marie-Tuta disease (SMT), a group of hereditary disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with STIs because so little is known about this condition.
About 23,000 people in the UK are presumed to have SMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and clenched toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich's (AF) ataxia - a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and would die before she turned 30.
The mother of two children, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others could.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I’ve never been able to ride roller skates or skateboard with other kids, and I had to be bullied a lot in school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten the feet, she looked into the medical record when her doctor came out of the room, and it was written that she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I put my nose where it should not be, and so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most horrific panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turned 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that interval.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease, because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a much lesser threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have SMT.
“When he explained what SMT was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK charity SMT has announced a month of information about SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on entrepreneurs in the Washington zone increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose moderately last year, as economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in County, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion into the state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses increased by 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when accounts declined in 2009 and 2010.
Taxes levied by the state rose 4.3 percent faster than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from taxes on entrepreneurs, while 36 percent of Maryland’s tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
In large part, tax revenue growth is driven by a return to the company’s previous property value level, researchers say, raising property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when the growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large proportion of these revenues come from large states such as California, New York, and Texas, the same seems to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in County, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012, up 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate has no similar effect on growth in state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of the company’s tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a nonprofit that doesn’t pay real estate taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center for Taxation.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the restoration of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs’ earnings also appear to be changing, according to this data.
Companies in the region have declared a state-wide corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, up $2.1 billion from 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the largest in the region.
Although the trends are in the same direction, the tax burden on entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three areas.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the country’s average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax in three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high - 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes on state- and local-level entrepreneurs and, overall, a more favorable tax climate for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is experiencing competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs up to 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to feel better and thus pay more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs, paid in the form of an individual income tax by small business owners - a transitional structure on which the majority of small firms are organized - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia grew by 20 percent to a rate of $2.4 billion last year.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with revenues from state and local income taxes rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington zone may be lagging behind, as a reduction in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
