Deputies proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of the initiative, data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The State Duma has submitted a draft law, which provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the base of legislative activity of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parahin ("Fair Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more rapid and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the protection of personal data and observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, which enters into force in a hurry parliamentarians, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians, processed through the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data of Russian citizens in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian legislation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "blacklists" of violating websites - the automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugova and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the KPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay for rent
Commenting on the draft law submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, Leonid Levin, said that he saw no problems with the transfer of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data repositories of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelecom", which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, Mail Group, behind the computer
“In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see any problems - they will be given technological opportunities for placement," Levin summed up.
The Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that if the bill was passed, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services of airline tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the draft law deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to establish a mechanism to inform the user of where the recording is being made, to systematize his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose in which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of such bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the decline of global services and significant economic losses.
