Savings certificate will make the name and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates on the originator, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban savings certificates on the applicant.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that savings certificates for the depositor do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since there is no need to deduct funds from the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The spiciness of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken due to small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and will suffer from it Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the profile market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASA, is that customers of a small bank who have purchased such a certificate, in case of withdrawal from it, the licenses try to get money in the ASA.
Some depositors, who do not have sufficient financial literacy and buy savings certificates for the depositor, may assume that their investments are insured.
The reasoned absence of insurance payments under these certificates in the case of withdrawal of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In practice, there were cases when the holders of the presenting certificates tried to seek insurance reimbursement through the court," the ASV said.
The problem, of course, is imaginary.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, because they have no right to compensation from the state.
If it were that the instrument is not insured in ASA, it would also prohibit metal bills, on which the funds of citizens are accounted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but their existence is not yet attempted.
The fact is, most likely, that the certificates for the originator are a very convenient security, which can actually act as a quasi-deneger.
At the same time, their movement is almost uncontrollable: any customer of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer to any citizen, and before the liquidation of such a certificate can change many owners.
It is not by chance that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be a named security, which must be stored in the depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of an irrevocable deposit is introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
