SCR stopped the investigation of the accident Tu-204 in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (SCR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the aircraft engineer.
Forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of approach to the landing, the failure of the crew to perform standard procedures on the landing, as well as the unintentional exit of the engines to the increased speed of direct thrust.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings, which followed the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at the Moscow airport Vnukovo.
The aircraft rolled over the runway and caught fire.
At the scene of the accident, the commander of the aircraft, a second pilot and a flight engineer were killed.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from their injuries.
Three more flight attendants, hospitalized with serious bodily injuries, were undergoing long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, which was moving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway, received serious bodily injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office after the crash conducted a check at the Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
