Anger is the most universal and functional human emotion.
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not random, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States have found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and can be read briefly about them in the press release of the University of California, Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face is shifted and lowered down the eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of lips, swollen nostrils - the same in all cultures, and make it even blind from birth children who have never seen it, says lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found out that this emotion has arisen to effectively manage disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he reports it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmations and another of their hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and move on to manual application, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer violent methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Relying on the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that create an angry facial expression should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus make the conflict as soon as possible agree with his conditions.
To verify this hypothesis, the researchers modeled on a computer the faces where each of the seven elements of the angry person was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the forwarded chin did not individually make the face ill, the stronger physical features of the person depicted in the study were recognized unanimously.
Human anger, as in animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to agree and obey.
A person inflates the nostrils and presses the lips with the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that shows its cheeks.
Anger is triggered by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that demonstrates the consequences of this refusal to the opposite side as effectively as possible.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tubby.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the television radio company "Crimea"
In 2014, the Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimea Television Radio Company".
This is stated in the draft decree of the government, prepared by the department, with which Lenta.ru became acquainted.
According to the explanatory note to the project, the subsidy from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment".
In particular, it is planned to re-equip the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server for the allocated money.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget foreseen for the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
